Text: ok, nevermind, I just figured it out!   :zany_face:   The answer is that the period "." in  the class name, is not actually part of the rule that carries over to the html file. so removing the period, which is what makes it a "class", is what it needed, and should not be included in the html file.  Hard lesson learned.  Thanks!
Text_raw: ok, nevermind, I just figured it out!   :zany_face:   The answer is that the period "." in  the class name, is not actually part of the rule that carries over to the html file. so removing the period, which is what makes it a "class", is what it needed, and should not be included in the html file.  Hard lesson learned.  Thanks!

Text:
Para poder "extraer" repositorios de una máquina remota, debes tener allí git instalado (para que reconozca los comandos git que enviarás) y con el repositorio actualmente configurado con git. Eso que indicas de que ya no lo usa pero originalmente fue creado así es un poco extraño.

En todo caso, en la documentación oficial cuentan un poco sobre cómo obtener un repositorio existente desde una máquina remota: https://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Git-Basics-Getting-a-Git-Repository
Text_raw:
Para poder "extraer" repositorios de una máquina remota, debes tener allí git instalado (para que reconozca los comandos git que enviarás) y con el repositorio actualmente configurado con git. Eso que indicas de que ya no lo usa pero originalmente fue creado así es un poco extraño.

En todo caso, en la documentación oficial cuentan un poco sobre cómo obtener un repositorio existente desde una máquina remota: <https://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Git-Basics-Getting-a-Git-Repository>

Text:
So `newObj` works in conjunction with `strArr` .
The Right Hand Side is evaluated, starting with the condition.
Lets go through the process:

`newObj[strArr[i]]` is checks for `b` in `newObj` . It doesn't exist so its false, so its `0`.
`0` is also false, so the whole grouping is `0`
add `0` plus `1`

Now you have 1 on the Right Hand Side, we assign `1` to the Left Hand Side
The Left Hand Side has `newObj[strArr[i]]` . Here we are using bracket notation to create a key.  In this case `b`
Assign `b : 1`

So now the object has `{b: 1}`
Text_raw:
So `newObj` works in conjunction with `strArr` .
The Right Hand Side is evaluated, starting with the condition.
Lets go through the process:

`newObj[strArr[i]]` is checks for `b` in `newObj` . It doesn't exist so its false, so its `0`.
`0` is also false, so the whole grouping is `0`
add `0` plus `1`

Now you have 1 on the Right Hand Side, we assign `1` to the Left Hand Side
The Left Hand Side has `newObj[strArr[i]]` . Here we are using bracket notation to create a key.  In this case `b`
Assign `b : 1`

So now the object has `{b: 1}`

Text:
Now when we iterate to the second `a` , things change.  Now the Right Hand Side
`(newObj[strArr[i]] || 0)` will already have a key `a` and it will be assigned a nonzero integer (truthy) value.
Since the value is truthy, the `0` in the OR statement is ignored.
The truthy value will then be incremented by `1` and assigned to the Left Hand Side

Text:
Hola, primero guardas en una variable el elemento del cual quieres tomar los valores:
```let myInput = document.getElementById("myInput").value```
Y luego le pasas el valor de ese input a tu card:
```document.getElementById("myCard").style.width = myInput+"px";```
Esto lo puedes poner dentro de una función, entonces cada vez que se llame a dicha función te cambiará el ancho de tu card dependiendo del valor que tenga el input. Lo mismo para height, solo cambias el input de donde traes el valor y el style.width lo cambias por style.height.

Todo esto podrías hacerlo con un addEventListener tipo change, entonces cada vez que escribas el valor en tu input este cambiará de tamaño tu card.
Text_raw:
Hola, primero guardas en una variable el elemento del cual quieres tomar los valores:
```let myInput = document.getElementById("myInput").value```
Y luego le pasas el valor de ese input a tu card:
```document.getElementById("myCard").style.width = myInput+"px";```
Esto lo puedes poner dentro de una función, entonces cada vez que se llame a dicha función te cambiará el ancho de tu card dependiendo del valor que tenga el input. Lo mismo para height, solo cambias el input de donde traes el valor y el style.width lo cambias por style.height.

Todo esto podrías hacerlo con un addEventListener tipo change, entonces cada vez que escribas el valor en tu input este cambiará de tamaño tu card.

Text:
Hi there, Rick, and thanks so much for your input.

As I generally code using either http://replit.comreplit.com>, or any other tool that allows me to test the result of my coding quickly (e. g., Quokka in _my_ VS Code), I tend to use `console.log()` to call my functions and test the results.

Now, when coding within a GitPod's workspace any of the 4Geeks Academy exercises, I am not using `console.log` to that purpose.

Let me get a couple of screenshots to clarify what I try to convey here.
Text_raw:
Hi there, Rick, and thanks so much for your input.

As I generally code using either <http://replit.com|replit.com>, or any other tool that allows me to test the result of my coding quickly (e. g., Quokka in _my_ VS Code), I tend to use `console.log()` to call my functions and test the results.

Now, when coding within a GitPod's workspace any of the 4Geeks Academy exercises, I am not using `console.log` to that purpose.

Let me get a couple of screenshots to clarify what I try to convey here.

Text:
Here we've got an approach for the exercise `20 Looping with FizzBuzz`.

In the first screenshot (http://replit.comreplit.com>), you may see the code and its result thru a `console.log()` calling the function.

This is the code:

```function fizzBuzz() {  
	for (let i = 1; i <= 100; i++) {
		if (i % 3 === 0 && i % 5 === 0) {
      console.log("FizzBuzz");
    } else if (i % 3 === 0) {
      console.log("Fizz");
    } else if (i % 5 === 0) {
      console.log("Buzz");
    } else {
      console.log(i)
    }
	} 
}

console.log(fizzBuzz());```

Here we've got an approach for the exercise `20 Looping with FizzBuzz`.

In the first screenshot (<http://replit.com|replit.com>), you may see the code and its result thru a `console.log()` calling the function.

This is the code:

```function fizzBuzz() {  
	for (let i = 1; i <= 100; i++) {
		if (i % 3 === 0 && i % 5 === 0) {
      console.log("FizzBuzz");
    } else if (i % 3 === 0) {
      console.log("Fizz");
    } else if (i % 5 === 0) {
      console.log("Buzz");
    } else {
      console.log(i)
    }
	} 
}

console.log(fizzBuzz());```

Text:
Dear Rick,

As I've moved on with pre-work exercises, I've finished the Excuse Generator, which can be now seen at https://ibaifernandez.github.io/excuse-generator/index.html

Now, there's a funny thing about it :slightly_smiling_face: As I open it in a Apple's computer's Google Chrome browser, I _experience_ it as it should be experienced —this is, as I meant it to be experienced. This is, an excuse _comes from_ the script on page load (`onload`) and another excuse substitutes that first excuse when you click on the button laid out to that purpose.

So far, so good.

Now, the thing is that I've opened that same URL on my buddy's computer (Microsoft Windows, not sure about the browser, though), and the experience is slightly different (as well as slightly frustrating). The thing is that, when opening such URL, the first excuse is loaded like in the previous case (`onload`), but when you click the button meant to generate a new excuse, two excuses are generated. The first one doesn't last for long on screen, and then the second one substitutes this first excuse.

I am suspicious about the fact that the page reloads once the user clicks on the button, so the excuse you see _for a quite short period of time_ is the excuse that you get `onclick`, and the second one is the one that gets loaded once the page immediately refreshes after clicking on such button. May that be so?

The question here would be:

*How to prevent the odd behavior on my buddy's (Microsoft) computer... if it goes all swell in my (Apple) computer?*

A ver, esto creo que se puede explicar así —estoy teniendo el mismo tema que @sebastnt.p— :

Tenemos dos botones en una barra de navegación. Uno es el de _grid_ y otro el de _feed_. Sin cambiar de URL (esto es, en la misma página), cuando clico el botón _grid_ quiero ver solo las fotos de 9 posts al estilo Instagram en forma de _grid_. Cuando clico el botón _feed_, quiero que me salgan los 9 posts con la información completa —_captions_, _likes_, etc.— al estilo de Instagram.

Así pues cada clic en cada uno de los botones descritos debe:

1. Hacer desaparecer el contenido _visible_ de la página en ese momento.
2. Hacer aparecer el contenido _oculto_ de la página.
Ejemplo:

Digamos que estoy en «modo _grid_». Hago clic en el botón «_feed_». Desaparecen las 9 fotos que hasta ese momento estaban siendo mostradas en un _grid_ de 3x3 y aparecen esas mismas 9 fotos cada una dentro de su _post_ correspondiente —con títulos, descripciones, _likes_ y demás, al estilo Instagram— en formato _feed_ —también al estilo Instagram.

Adjunto captura de la vista _feed_. Lo que @sebastnt.p y yo estamos tratando es que, al clicar el botón _grid_ que está sobre los posts, desparezca esta vista «tipo feed» y aparezca una vista «tipo _grid_» de 3x3 solo con las fotos —nada de título, descripción o likes—.

Text:
Hi, @amiramandisbaa.

It is asking you to list every file within every folder. Think of a nested list:

1. 1st folder
    a. 1st subfolder
        i. 1st file of the 1st subfolder
        ii. 2nd file of the 1st subfolder
        iii. 3rd file of the 1st subfolder
    b. 2nd subfolder
        i. 1st subfolder of the 2nd subfolder
            1. 1st file of the 1st subfolder of the 2nd subfolder
        ii. 1st file of the 2nd subfolder
        iii. 2nd file of the 2nd subfolder
        iv. 3rd file of the 2nd subfolder
    c. 3rd subfolder
        i. 1st file of the 3rd subfolder
        ii. 2nd file of the 3rd subfolder
        iii. 3rd file of the 3rd subfolder
    d. 1st file of the 1st folder
What the exercise is asking you is to list all of that recursively respecting the hierarchy.

You should get a list such as...

• 1st folder
• 1st subfolder
• 1st file of the 1st subfolder
• 2nd file of the 1st subfolder
• 3rd file of the 1st subfolder
• 2nd subfolder
• 1st subfolder of the 2nd subfolder
• 1st file of the 1st subfolder of the 2nd subfolder
• 1st file of the 2nd subfolder
• 2nd file of the 2nd subfolder
• 3rd file of the 2nd subfolder
• 3rd subfolder
• 1st file of the 3rd subfolder
• 2nd file of the 3rd subfolder
• 3rd file of the 3rd subfolder
• 1st file of the 1st folder
Which basically is all files and folders listed in hierarchic order.

I believe this is a good article to fully understand the concept :slightly_smiling_face:

https://www.cyberciti.biz/faq/how-to-show-recursive-directory-listing-on-linux-or-unix/

Cheers! :clinking_glasses:

Awesome! Thanks :slightly_smiling_face:

Now, on a different note...

> An `.scss` file is *a style sheet that contains Sass language*. It is similar to a `.css` file but with added capabilities, such as variables, nested rules, and mix-ins. `.scss` files are used to format webpage contents. `.scss` files are stored in a plain text format.
Then, in this case, the questions would be:

1. What does "Sass language" mean in practical terms?
2. Are those "added capabilities" programmed using any other language besides CSS itself?

Text:
`06` Practicing Rules
:memo: Instructions:
1. Set this URL as the background image of the page, and repeat it vertically only: `../../.learn/assets/background-vertical.jpg?raw=true`
2. Change the font-family of the `h1` to `Courier` and the rest of the website to `Times new Roman`.
3. Change the color of `h1` to `red`.
4. Make all the `h2's` with an `underline`.
5. Add a `left padding` to the whole document of `20px` to make it easier to read.
6. Add a white `semi-transparent background (0.2)` to the `first paragraph` to make it easier to read (you have tu use `rgba` for that) and write down "3 reasons you know you are learning".
7. Then apply a `padding` of `5px` to all sides of that paragraph.
8. Change the `anchor` "hover" color to `green` and remove the underline (you have to actually hover the anchor to test it).

Text:
Hi there, @aleperixx, @tgonzalez, and everybody else who's reading.

For what it may be worth, and according to what I kept on researching yesterday, the solution to the problem lies in the fact that Webpack

>  take[s] ./src/index.js as the default!
*Source* (see attached screenshot): https://stackoverflow.com/questions/49772863/webpack-4-error-in-entry-module-not-found-error-cant-resolve-src

So either the .js file that we want to use as the entry point is called `index.js`, and it's in the `./src/` path or _things blow up_.

Now, if we want the entry point to be different from the one taken by WebPack by default, we have two possible solutions:

*First solution*

_Tweaking_ a bit our `package.json`, right where we define the script that we usually call `"build"`. In this case, what needs to be done is to add an entry point after the `"webpack"` value. That is, it should end up like this:

```"scripts": {
         "test": "echo \"Error: no test specified\" && exit 1",
         "build": "webpack [entry point]"
     },```
Or, for example, if we were using the `app.js` file in the root of our document:

```"scripts": {
         "test": "echo \"Error: no test specified\" && exit 1",
         "build": "webpack ./app.js"
     },```
*Second solution*

The second solution is to start by adding the configuration file `webpack.config.js` to the root of our project. Within, we'll need to add:

```module.exports = {
     entry: "./app.js",
};```
And, for starters, that would solve the enormous error that I showed in the main message of this thread, as well as the first question, which was:

> *What is that error yielded on the Terminal saying?*
So what the error is saying - correct me if I am wrong - is that there is no `index.js` file to resolve in the `./src/` path—or, said differently, that `./src/index.js` doesn't exist.

I still can't find a concrete explanation for the second question; This is:

> *Why can't that error be solved by changing the `"main": "index.js"` to `"main": "app.js"`, or to `"main": "./src/app.js"`?*
The respective answers to the third and fourth questions are also already obvious. That is:

>  *3.- Why the only solution I've found by myself implies adding an _entry point_ to my `"build"`?*
The answer would be:

Because, indeed, it is one of the possible solutions.

And...

>  *Is it _logical_ to add an _entry point_ to my `"build"`?*
Well, I assume that it is logical because, once again, WebPack defaults to `./src/index.js` as its entry point.

Now, regarding questions 5 and 6, my doubts remain, in case you are kind enough to find an answer to share.

Thanks!

https://developer.mozilla.org/es/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/String/split

Text:
:memo: Instructions:
1. Set this URL as the background image of the page, and repeat it vertically only: `../../.learn/assets/background-vertical.jpg?raw=true`
2. Change the font-family of the `h1` to `Courier` and the rest of the website to `Times new Roman`.
3. Change the color of `h1` to `red`.
4. Make all the `h2's` with an `underline`.
5. Add a `left padding` to the whole document of `20px` to make it easier to read.
6. Add a white `semi-transparent background (0.2)` to the `first paragraph` to make it easier to read (you have to use `rgba` for that) and write down "3 reasons you know you are learning".
7. Then apply a `padding` of `5px` to all sides of that paragraph.
8. Change the `anchor` "hover" color to `green` and remove the underline (you have to actually hover the anchor to test it).
Text_raw:
:memo: Instructions:
1. Set this URL as the background image of the page, and repeat it vertically only: `../../.learn/assets/background-vertical.jpg?raw=true`
2. Change the font-family of the `h1` to `Courier` and the rest of the website to `Times new Roman`.
3. Change the color of `h1` to `red`.
4. Make all the `h2's` with an `underline`.
5. Add a `left padding` to the whole document of `20px` to make it easier to read.
6. Add a white `semi-transparent background (0.2)` to the `first paragraph` to make it easier to read (you have to use `rgba` for that) and write down "3 reasons you know you are learning".
7. Then apply a `padding` of `5px` to all sides of that paragraph.
8. Change the `anchor` "hover" color to `green` and remove the underline (you have to actually hover the anchor to test it).

Sí no te interesa conservar el resto del array, usa splice:

Text: Hello Celeste!You should eliminate array.length in the method splice. The second argument in splice() tells how many items to eliminate. If you write: let array1=array.splice(n), you´ll delete from the item n until the end of the array and put them in array1. I hope i helped you
Text_raw: Hello Celeste!You should eliminate array.length in the method splice. The second argument in splice() tells how many items to eliminate. If you write: let array1=array.splice(n), you´ll delete from the item n until the end of the array and put them in array1. I hope i helped you
